# The Nature of Work: From Entropy to Algorithm by C Raynor

**A Chapter on the Full Evolution of Human Labor, Its Organization, Its Destruction, and the Class Structures That Will Emerge from the Age of Artificial Intelligence**

---

## I. What Work Is — Before It Became a Job

Any serious examination of labor organization must begin before labor was organized — before it was even conceived of as something separable from life itself. The anthropologist James Suzman, in *Work: A Deep History, from the Stone Age to the Age of Robots* (2021), offers the most radical reframing of the question available in contemporary scholarship: work, at its most fundamental level, is the negentropic capture and conversion of free energy into usable energy.[^1] Every living organism does it. Every cell does it. The universe, Suzman argues, is structured to favor entropy — the dissipation of energy — and life itself exists as a mechanism to accelerate that process.

This is not a metaphor. It is physics applied to anthropology. And it demolishes the foundational assumption of classical economics — what Suzman calls "the problem of scarcity" — the idea that human beings are driven by insatiable desires in a world of insufficient resources, and therefore must toil endlessly to survive.

The anthropological record tells a different story. Suzman's fieldwork among the Ju/'hoansi (Khoisan peoples) of southern Africa, and the broader cross-cultural record of hunter-gatherer societies, reveals what Marshall Sahlins called "the original affluent society": groups whose members worked roughly fifteen hours per week to meet their material needs, maintained egalitarian social structures built on "demand sharing" (where it was rude to refuse a request, not rude to make one), and experienced no meaningful distinction between "work" and "leisure."[^2] For 95% of our species' history, work did not occupy anything like the place in human life that it occupies now.[^3]

The critical transition — the one that made everything after it possible, including unions, factories, exploitation, and AI — was the agricultural revolution, approximately 10,000 years ago. Suzman demonstrates that farming did not emerge because it was better than foraging. It was, in nearly every measurable way, worse: more hours of labor, more monotonous tasks, worse nutrition, greater vulnerability to famine and disease. But it produced surpluses, and surpluses created something new — the capacity for accumulation, hierarchy, and the separation of those who worked from those who controlled the products of that work.[^4]

As Suzman notes, the words "cattle" and "capital" share the same etymological root. They mean the same thing. When we speak of capital growth, the metaphor is a herd of cows.[^5] The entire vocabulary of modern economics is rooted in the agricultural transformation of human labor from a communal, integrated activity into a separable, controllable commodity.

This is where Marx enters — not as a political radical, but as the first theorist to fully articulate what the agricultural revolution and its industrial successor had done to the human relationship with work.

