## III. The Rise of Organized Labor: From Conspiracy to Power (1794–1955)

The history of labor organization in America is the history of workers attempting to resist these alienations — first informally, then through collective structures that the state and capital fought relentlessly to destroy.

The earliest recorded American strike occurred in 1768 when New York journeymen tailors protested a wage reduction. The first sustained trade union, the Federal Society of Journeymen Cordwainers, was formed in Philadelphia in 1794.[^11] For the next century, organizing was dangerous and frequently treated by courts as criminal conspiracy. Employers used violence, lockouts, retaliatory firings, and strikebreakers with minimal legal restraint.[^12]

The breakthrough came during the Great Depression. The massive wave of organizing and strikes in the 1930s forced the Roosevelt administration to pass the **National Labor Relations Act (NLRA) of 1935**, establishing a legal framework for union elections, collective bargaining, and the right to strike.[^13] The CIO's industrial unionism brought mass-production workers — auto, steel, meatpacking, electrical — into the labor movement for the first time. Union membership surged from 2.8 million in 1933 to 14 million by 1945, covering roughly 36% of the non-farm workforce.[^14] By the mid-1950s, approximately one in three American workers was unionized.[^15]

This was the peak. It lasted, in its full force, approximately one decade.

