## IV. The Powell Memo and the Organized Destruction of Labor Power (1947–Present)

The decline of organized labor in America was not an accident of globalization or technological change. It was a project — deliberate, funded, and strategically executed over decades. The intellectual blueprint was provided by a single document.

### The Taft-Hartley Act (1947)

The first blow came just twelve years after the NLRA's passage. The **Labor Management Relations Act of 1947** (Taft-Hartley) prohibited secondary boycotts, outlawed closed shops, authorized states to pass "right-to-work" laws, and required union leaders to sign affidavits swearing they were not Communist sympathizers.[^16] This last provision was weaponized during "Operation Dixie," the campaign to organize the non-unionized South. Anti-union forces in the region used accusations of communism and the threat of racial desegregation to crush the campaign. The Southern textile industry remained un-unionized — a failure whose consequences persist today in the geography of Amazon's most successful anti-union campaigns.[^17]

### The Powell Memorandum (1971)

On August 23, 1971, Lewis F. Powell Jr., a corporate attorney and Philip Morris board member, sent a confidential memorandum to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce titled "Attack on American Free Enterprise System." Two months later, President Nixon nominated him to the Supreme Court.[^18]

The memo argued that the American economic system was "under broad attack" from consumer, labor, and environmental groups. Powell urged a coordinated corporate response across every institution of American life: universities, media, courts, and legislatures. He recommended building networks of scholars-on-call to defend capitalism, monitoring and critiquing media coverage, and constructing legal organizations to fight regulatory and labor protections in court.[^19]

The memo was a blueprint, and corporate America built from it. The Heritage Foundation was established in 1973. The American Legislative Exchange Council followed. The Cato Institute and American Enterprise Institute were revived and massively expanded.[^20] In 1970, only a handful of Fortune 500 companies had public affairs offices in Washington. By 1980, more than 80% did. In 1974, labor unions accounted for half of all political action committee (PAC) money. By 1980, unions accounted for less than a fourth.[^21]

As Robert Reich has summarized: Powell's memo argued that consumer, labor, and environmental groups were attacking the free enterprise system. In reality, these groups were enforcing the implicit social contract that had emerged after World War II — ensuring corporations were responsive to all their stakeholders, not just shareholders. But Powell and the Chamber saw it differently, and they mobilized for political combat.[^22]

Powell then used his position on the Supreme Court to advance the same agenda judicially, laying the groundwork for decisions that would culminate in *Citizens United v. FEC* (2010), which granted corporations the right to spend unlimited sums on political campaigns.[^23]

### The Reagan Fracture and After

With the inauguration of Ronald Reagan in 1981, the ideological alliance of corporate libertarians consolidated control. Reagan broke the PATCO air traffic controllers' strike, establishing the precedent that the federal government would side with employers against organized labor.[^24] Between 1975 and 1985, union membership fell by 5 million. In manufacturing, the unionized share of the workforce dropped below 25%.[^25]

The Economic Policy Institute's comprehensive analysis demonstrates that **at most one-fifth** of the decline in union density can be attributed to the erosion of manufacturing. The decline occurred across every private-sector industry — utilities, transportation, construction, mining, communications — and was driven primarily by legal obstruction, employer aggression, and political choices.[^26] While 86% of workers who voted for a union won a first contract in the 1950s, by the 1990s only 56% did.[^27]

By 2024, private-sector union membership had fallen to under 6%, despite Gallup polls showing 70% public approval of unions — the highest since the mid-1960s.[^28] The demand for collective bargaining has not eroded. The capacity to achieve it has been systematically destroyed.

