## VI. Amazon, the Algorithm, and the Death on the Floor

This is the context in which a man collapsed and died on the floor of Amazon's PDX9 warehouse in Troutdale, Oregon, on April 6, 2026, while his coworkers were told to keep working.

A CPR-trained employee begged to help the woman performing chest compressions. Her supervisor, weeping, told her it had to be management or the safety team, and to turn around and get back to work.[^38] Workers continued loading trucks for over an hour while the body lay on the floor. Supervisors did not tell all employees someone had died. That evening, a text went out: report to work as usual the next day.[^39]

Amazon's injury rate was, at the time of this incident, 80% higher than the company's own reduction target. The serious injury rate was nearly double that of non-Amazon warehouses: 5.9 per 100 workers versus 3.0 per 100 at competitors.[^40] Crucially, Amazon's robotic fulfillment centers — the ones with the most advanced technology — had *higher* injury rates than non-robotic facilities, because the robots set the pace and management monitored workers' speed in real-time, logging any lag as "time off task."[^41]

By mid-2025, Amazon had deployed over one million robots across more than 300 fulfillment centers — approaching parity with its approximately 1.5 million human workforce.[^42] Leaked internal documents revealed plans to automate 75% of operations and eliminate roughly 600,000 positions over the next several years. The documents recommended avoiding the terms "automation" and "AI" when discussing these plans publicly.[^43]

The JFK8 warehouse in Staten Island remains, as of April 2026, the only NLRB-recognized unionized Amazon facility in the United States. It took four years of legal obstruction before the NLRB issued a bargaining order forcing Amazon to recognize the union.[^44] Amazon spent $14 million on anti-union consultants in 2022 alone, and the broader cost of its anti-union legal and consulting apparatus over four years is estimated in the hundreds of millions.[^45]

