## VII. The Class Structure That Is Emerging

The question is no longer whether AI will reshape the class structure. It already has. The question is what the new classes will look like, who will populate them, and what their lives will be.

### The Hourglass Economy

MIT economist David Autor's research on "job polarization" documents what has already occurred over the past four decades: computers eliminated a vast range of middle-skill jobs in manufacturing and offices that once provided stable livelihoods for Americans without college degrees. The Digital Revolution, contrary to the utopian vision that it would flatten economic hierarchies by democratizing information, has done the opposite. As Autor writes: "Information, it turns out, is merely an input into a more consequential economic function, decision-making, which is the province of elite experts."[^46]

The result has been an hourglass economy: well-compensated decision-making roles at the top, low-paid service roles at the bottom, and a hollowed-out middle. Those without a bachelor's degree — some 60% of American adults — have been pushed into non-expert service roles with limited advancement, no benefits, and precarious scheduling.[^47]

The World Economic Forum's *Future of Jobs Report 2025* projects that job disruption will affect up to 22% of jobs by 2030, with middle-income positions bearing the brunt of losses.[^48] The Federal Reserve reports that the top 10% of Americans now hold 70% of national wealth, while the middle-class share has fallen from 62% in 1980 to 43% in 2023.[^49] The Economic Policy Institute shows that between 1979 and 2022, labor productivity grew 64.6%, while worker compensation grew just 17.3%.[^50]

### The New Classes

Based on current trajectories and the scholarship reviewed here, the emerging class structure can be described in roughly four tiers:

**The Capital-Algorithm Class.** Owners of AI systems, data infrastructure, patents, and platform monopolies. This is a vanishingly small group — the top 0.1% — whose wealth derives not from labor but from ownership of the machines that replace labor. Their ranks include the owners of tech platforms, pharmaceutical patents, energy infrastructure, and financial instruments. Their lives are geographically untethered, legally insulated, and politically dominant through the mechanisms the Powell Memo helped construct.

**The Expert-Decision Class.** Professionals whose work involves judgment, creativity, and complex decision-making that AI augments rather than replaces: physicians, senior engineers, legal strategists, research scientists, senior managers. This group — perhaps 15-20% of the workforce — will see its productivity enhanced by AI tools, and in Autor's optimistic scenario, AI could actually expand this class by enabling less-credentialed workers to perform decision-making functions previously reserved for elite experts.[^51] Whether this scenario materializes depends entirely on policy choices that, as of this writing, are moving in the opposite direction.

**The Maintenance-Service Class.** Workers who maintain, repair, clean, feed, care for, and physically manage the systems and human beings that the algorithm cannot reach: nurses, electricians, plumbers, warehouse technicians, childcare workers, food service workers. This class will remain large, but its working conditions will be defined by algorithmic scheduling, real-time surveillance, and the elimination of employer-provided benefits. These are the workers who already populate Amazon's warehouses, DoorDash's delivery fleet, and the home healthcare agencies that employ millions. Their lives will be characterized by unpredictable schedules, no retirement security, limited healthcare, and the constant threat of replacement by the next incremental improvement in robotics.

**The Displaced-Precariat.** Workers whose functions have been fully automated and who lack the credentials, capital, or geographic mobility to transition into other roles. This class will disproportionately include older workers in manufacturing regions, younger workers without college degrees in service economies, and — as Amazon's own data shows — Black workers, who are overrepresented in the warehouse roles most immediately subject to automation.[^52] Their lives will be defined by gig-economy piecework, public assistance (if it still exists in its current form), and the psychological toll of purposelessness that Suzman identifies as the deepest risk of the automated future.

### What Their Lives Will Look Like

For the Expert-Decision Class, life will superficially resemble the current upper-middle-class professional lifestyle, but with a sharper edge: AI tools will raise productivity expectations, eliminate junior colleagues who once shared the workload, and create what a 2024 McKinsey report identified as the "vanishing entry rung" — the elimination of the junior positions through which professionals historically built skills and advanced.[^53] Senior workers will be more productive and more isolated.

For the Maintenance-Service Class, the defining experience will be algorithmic management without the possibility of appeal. The supervisor with tears in her eyes at PDX9 — the one who told Sam to turn around and not look — represents the transitional figure: a human being executing decisions that have already been encoded in the system. In the near future, there will be no supervisor to cry. There will be an app notification.

For the Displaced-Precariat, the political scientist Peter Turchin's framework of "elite overproduction" and "popular immiseration" becomes relevant. Turchin's model, applied through AI-driven analysis, predicts that growing inequality, combined with an oversupply of credentialed workers competing for a shrinking number of meaningful positions, will produce severe social instability — a prediction he made before the current AI disruption and which current trajectories are accelerating.[^54]

